            <h2>FAQs</h2>
            <h3>What facilities are available for international arrivals at Cleveland Hopkins International Airport?</h3>
            <p>Cleveland Hopkins has a dedicated Federal Inspection Services (FIS) customs and border protection facility located in Concourse A. This facility is designed to streamline customs procedures for passengers arriving from international destinations.</p>
            <h3>Which airlines operate from the various concourses at the airport?</h3>
            <p>Concourse A: Serves Frontier, Spirit, charter flights, and all international arrivals, with Delta Air Lines using it for overflow.</p>
            <p>Concourse B: Primarily serves Delta and Southwest Airlines.</p>
            <p>Concourse C: Hosts Air Canada Express, Alaska Airlines, American Airlines, JetBlue, and United Airlines (excluding international arrivals).</p>
            <p>Concourse D: Currently not in use since 2014.</p>
            <h3>What renovations are planned for Cleveland Hopkins International Airport?</h3>
            <p>A $2 billion renovation project is in discussion, aimed at expanding security and check-in counters, enhancing the checked baggage inspection system, increasing gate waiting areas, and adding eight new gates. The plans include renovations for Concourses A and C, rebuilding Concourse B, and constructing a new concourse to replace the vacant Concourse D.</p>
            <h3>What amenities can passengers expect to find at the airport?</h3>
            <p>The airport offers a variety of dining and retail options managed by Cleveland Airmall, featuring venues like Great Lakes Brewing Company, Bar Symon, and the Rock &amp; Roll Hall of Fame Museum Store. Additionally, there are two lounges: a United Club in Concourse C and The Club CLE near Concourse B.</p>
            <h3>How many runways does the airport have, and what are their dimensions?</h3>
            <p>Cleveland Hopkins has three runways:</p>
            <p>06R/24L: 9,953 ft (3,034 m)</p>
            <p>06L/24R: 9,000 ft (2,743 m)</p>
            <p>10/28: 6,018 ft (1,834 m)</p>
            <p>These runways accommodate a variety of aircraft, supporting the airport's extensive operations.</p>
            <h3>Is there hotel accommodation available near the airport for layovers?</h3>
            <p>The Sheraton Hotel on airport grounds, which previously provided layover accommodations, closed in June 2022. The airport plans to demolish the building in 2024. Passengers will need to find nearby hotels for overnight stays.</p>
            <h3>What is the history of Concourse D, and why is it currently not in use?</h3>
            <p>Concourse D was built in 1999 and initially served smaller regional aircraft. However, it became vacant in 2014 when United Airlines consolidated operations to Concourse C after closing its hub. Future plans include replacing Concourse D with a new concourse as part of the airport's renovation efforts.</p>
